==English==

===Etymology===
Middle English ''meek'', [[meke]], borrowed from a Scandinavian source such as Old Norse [[mjúkr]], "soft". Erroniously "soft" because the Scriptures state that Moses was the "meekest among men".  He was anything but "soft".  It means to know the limits of ones response to an event and the ability to choose the proper response to fit the even.  Killing the 3,000 golden calf worshipers was a demonstration of "meekness".  So was the realization that Aaron, rather than he, would better serve the demands of the moment.  Rather than an attempt to evade the requirements from Jehovah, he recognized that his older brother Aaron would be more fitting.  Ironically, it was Aaron who appeased the people in the making of the calf and then was the one to lead the assalt upon the image worshippers.  Aaron was not "meek" and  Moses was anything but "soft". This is a classic case of where General Semantics calls us to investigate how the object manifested in Moses could become something that was anything but "soft".  How did that occur?

